# Planogram agent workflow

This rule applies to **this repo only**. Prefer small, reviewable changes.

## Before starting work

1. Via **Linear MCP** (workspace `planogram`, team **Planogram** / `PLA`, project **Planogram**): find the issue; confirm status and sprint membership (Todo vs Backlog).
2. Prefer an existing Linear issue over inventing chat-only todos; put work in **Todo** before coding.
3. Do not maintain a parallel roadmap in the repo — Linear is the only development plan.

## Linear (sole source of truth)

- Linear owns scope, priority, status, acceptance criteria, and sprint membership.
- Project: https://linear.app/planogram/project/planogram
- Statuses: `Backlog` → `Todo` → `In Progress` → `In Review` → `Done` (or `Canceled` / `Duplicate`).
- Coding → **In Progress**; PR open → **In Review**; merged to `main` → **Done**.
- Issues need enough context: goal, acceptance criteria, out of scope, links.
- Use the Linear project doc **Issue template**, or `docs/LINEAR_ISSUE_TEMPLATE.md`.
- Follow **Delivery conventions** (Linear project doc) for issue titles, branch names, commits, and PRs — see `.cursor/rules/delivery-conventions.mdc`.
- Labels: feature / bug / chore / debt when useful.
- Create a Linear issue before starting any new planned work.

## Sprints

- Define sprint membership in Linear only (Todo = this sprint, Backlog = later).
- Prefer ~3–6 Todo issues at a time.
- Do not duplicate sprint tables or roadmaps in markdown.

## GitHub (`main` is protected)

- Never commit directly to `main`. Use a feature branch: `pla-<N>-<short-kebab-slug>` (see delivery conventions).
- Open a PR into `main` when work is ready (`gh pr create`). Title: `<Summary> (PLA-N).`; body: Summary, Test plan, and `PLA-N`.
- Commits: `<Summary>. (PLA-N).` — imperative, present tense.
- No force-push to `main`; do not bypass branch protection.

## Design system

- UI follows `docs/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md` (semantic tokens, thin UI, engine is truth for mm).

## After finishing

1. Linear: **In Review** (PR open) → **Done** (merged), unless waiting on review.
2. Keep any technical docs under `docs/` accurate and linked from the Linear issue when relevant.
